'''Ebrahimali Abubacker Siddiq''' is an Indian agricultural scientist, whose research in [[genetics]] and [[plant breeding]] is reported to have assisted in the development of various high-yielding rice varieties such as dwarf [[basmati]] and hybrid rice.<ref name="ABF">{{cite web | url=http://www.abfindia.org/PeopleECMSiddiq.aspx | title=ABF | publisher=ABF | date=2014 | accessdate=November 22, 2014}}</ref> The government of India honored Siddiq in 2011 with the fourth-highest civilian award of [[Padma Shri]].<ref name="Padma Shri">{{cite web | url=http://mha.nic.in/sites/upload_files/mha/files/LST-PDAWD-2013.pdf | title=Padma Shri | publisher=Padma Shri | date=2014 | accessdate=November 11, 2014}}</ref>

==Biography==
{{quotebox|align = right|width=21em|''With the climate change already costing farmers with decreasing crop yields (up to 10 per cent) and new crop land constraints, efforts should be made to develop hybrid varieties that can withstand physical stresses, including water submergence during severe monsoon, drought and high salinity'', says E. A. Siddiq.<ref name="Business Standard">{{cite web | url=http://www.business-standard.com/article/current-affairs/need-to-try-non-conventional-methods-in-agri-114020301255_1.html | title=Business Standard | publisher=Business Standard | date=February 3, 2014 | accessdate=November 22, 2014}}</ref>}}

E. A. Siddiq was born in 1937 in Hyderabad, the capital of the present day state of [[Telengana]], India.<ref name="INSA">{{cite web | url=http://www.insaindia.org/detail.php?id=N95-1187 | title=INSA | publisher=INSA | date=2014 | accessdate=November 22, 2014}}</ref> His graduate studies were completed in Botany (1959)<ref name="INSA" /> from the [[University of Madras]]<ref name="Omics Group">{{cite web | url=http://omicsgroup.com/conferences/agricultural-horticultural-2014/speaker-popup.php?member=b&id=1871 | title=Omics Group | publisher=Omics Group | date=2014 | accessdate=November 22, 2014}}</ref> following which he obtained masters (1964)<ref name="INSA" /> and doctoral degrees (1968)<ref name="INSA" /> in [[Cytogenetics]], under the supervision of renowned botanist, [[M. S. Swaminathan]], from the [[Indian Agricultural Research Institute]] (IARI).<ref name="ABF" /><ref name="CDFD">{{cite web | url=http://www.cdfd.org.in/labpages/e_a_saddiq.html | title=CDFD | publisher=Centre for DNA Finger printing and Diagnostics | date=2014 | accessdate=November 22, 2014}}</ref> His career started at his alma mater, the Indian Agricultural Research Institute, as a cytogeneticist in 1968,<ref name="Padmashree Prof Dr E A Siddiq">{{cite web | url=http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=J4S5vckzsqY | title=Padmashree Prof Dr E A Siddiq | publisher=YouTube | work=Video | date=10 February 2014 | accessdate=November 22, 2014}}</ref><ref name="ABF" /><ref name="CDFD" /> a post he held till 1976 when he was promoted as the Senior Scientist.<ref name="INSA" /><ref name="ABF" /><ref name="CDFD" /> In 1983, he was deputed to Egypt as the Rice Breeder and in 1986, he was transferred to Philippines as the Professor of Genetics.<ref name="ABF" /> The next year, in 1987, he returned to India as the Project Director of the [[Directorate of Rice Research]], Hyderabad<ref name="Omics Group" /> and worked there till 1994.<ref name="INSA" /><ref name="ABF" /> The next move was to [[Indian Council of Agricultural Research]] (ICAR), New Delhi as the Deputy Director General of the Crop Science Division.<ref name="Omics Group" /><ref name="CDFD" /><ref name="Zoom Info" />

In 1997 Siddiq was honored as the National Professor of ICAR and in 2002,<ref name="ABF" /><ref name="Padmashree Prof Dr E A Siddiq" /><ref name="Zoom Info">{{cite web | url=http://www.zoominfo.com/s/#!search/profile/person?personId=17977138&targetid=profile | title=Zoom Info | publisher=Zoom Info | date=2014 | accessdate=November 22, 2014}}</ref> he took charge of the [[Centre for DNA Fingerprinting and Diagnostics]] (CDFD) as the Distinguished Chair.<ref name="INSA" /><ref name="CDFD" /> On his retirement in 2007, he was appointed as the Adjunct Scientist at CFFD.<ref name="INSA" /> He also holds the positions of Adjunct Professor of the [[University of Hyderabad]], Adjunct Professor of the Indian Agricultural Research Institute (IARI) and the Honorary Professor of Biotechnology at [[Acharya NG Ranga Agricultural University]], Hyderabad.<ref name="INSA" /><ref name="ABF" /><ref name="CDFD" />

==Positions==
Siddiq was a member of the scientific advisory council of the [[Prime Minister of India]] from 2004 to 2009.<ref name="Zoom Info" /><ref name="ABF" /> He sits in the Board of Members of the [[International Rice Research Institute]]<ref name="Zoom Info" /> as well as the Executive Committee of the Agri Biotech Foundation.<ref name="ABF" /> He was a member of the working group for the Eleventh Five Year Plan (2007-2012) of India.<ref name="Planning Commission">{{cite web | url=http://webcache.googleusercontent.com/search?q=cache:http://planningcommission.nic.in/aboutus/committee/wrkgrp11/wrk11_1i.htm | title=Planning Commission | publisher=Planning Commission | date=2007 | accessdate=November 22, 2014}}</ref> He was also a member of the Research Advisory Committee of the National Research Centre on Plant Biotechnology, an Indian Council of Agricultural Research (ICAR) subsidiary.<ref name="NRCPB">{{cite web | url=http://nrcpb.org/content/research-advisory-committee-172011-3062014 | title=NRCPB | publisher=NRCPB | date=2014 | accessdate=November 22, 2014}}</ref>

Siddiq is the chairman of the Farm and Rural Science Foundation of [[The Federation of Andhra Pradesh Chambers of Commerce and Industry]].<ref name="Hybiz TV" /> He also served as a council member of National Science academy, India from 1998 till 2000.<ref name="INSA" />

==Legacy==
Siddiq is credited with contributions on the scientific, academic and organizational fronts.<ref name="CDFD" /> His research primarily focusses on genetic research and applied breeding of rice, for improving the yield and quality, and is reported to have assisted in the development of ten high-yielding rice varieties.<ref name="INSA" /><ref name="CDFD" /> A variety of dwarf basmati rice (Pusa Basmati-1), claimed to be the first high-yielding variety in its class,<ref name="ABF" /> and quick maturing varieties such as Pusa 2-21, Pusa 33, Pusa 4 and Pusa 834 are credited to Siddiq.<ref name="CDFD" /><ref name="INSA" /> His contribution is also reported in the development of DRRH-1, a first-generation Indian hybrid.<ref name="CDFD" /><ref name="INSA" /> Siddiq has also done basic research on adaptability, stability and the potential of convergent breeding of various rice breeds. His research has also covered the cytogenetic and phylogenetic aspects of rice breeding.<ref name="CDFD" />

Siddiq was a part of the project for enhancement of rice research in Egypt, under the USAID-funded Rice Breeder programme of [[International Rice Research Institute]] (IRRI) in 1987 as well as in the establishment of the [[Government of India]]-sponsored National Rice Research Institute in Vietnam.<ref name="CDFD" /><ref name="INSA" /> Working as a consultant for the [[World Bank]], he has designed the projects for agricultural development in Assam and Bangladesh.<ref name="INSA" /> He is credited with two scientific studies, one in Egypt and the other in India, in the capacity of the consultant to the [[Food and Agricultural Organization]] (FAO).<ref name="CDFD" />

On the organizational front, Siddiq has collaborated with the World Bank/[[Food and Agriculture Organization|FAO]] as consultant and advisor and has prepared many project proposals for programs in Egypt, Sri Lanka, India, Indonesia and the Philippines.<ref name="INSA" /><ref name="CDFD" /> He has also helped in the establishment of rice research institutes in Vietnam and Bangladesh. He was a member of the Task Force on Crop Biotechnology, Monitoring and Evaluation Committee and the National Convenor of the Natural Rice Biotechnology Network during the period from 1990 to 2002.<ref name="INSA" /><ref name="CDFD" />

Siddiq is credited with over 150 research publications,<ref name="INSA" /><ref name="CDFD" /><ref name="FAO">{{cite web | url=http://www.fao.org/docrep/003/X6905e/x6905e09.htm | title=Bridging the Rice Yield Gap in India | publisher=Food and Agriculture Organization | work=Scientific paper | date=2014 | accessdate=November 22, 2014}}</ref><ref name="Omics Group" /> 16 of which have been listed by [[Microsoft Academic Search]] in their online repository<ref name="Microsoft Academic Search">{{cite web | url=http://65.54.113.26/Author/42429567/ebrahimali-siddiq | title=Microsoft Academic Search | publisher=Microsoft Academic Search | date=2014 | accessdate=November 22, 2014}}</ref> and his research findings have been cited in many books and journals.<ref name="Chemical Aspects of Rice Grain Quality">{{cite web | url=http://books.google.ae/books?id=hAh_3eYATMwC&pg=PA147&lpg=PA147&dq=E.+A.+Siddiq&source=bl&ots=PRaCFDsphM&sig=FnMyEsuF48NUgOL1ctnoJxf_Kqk&hl=en&sa=X&ei=aLtwVKP4KYbDOcuTgcgI&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=E.%20A.%20Siddiq&f=false | title=Chemical Aspects of Rice Grain Quality | publisher=IRRI | date=1979 | accessdate=November 22, 2014}}</ref><ref name="Breaking the Yield Barrier">{{cite web | url=http://books.google.ae/books?id=2ZrpO5UH4UMC&pg=PA18&lpg=PA18&dq=E.+A.+Siddiq&source=bl&ots=Ex1n84Dt4V&sig=WtbdPSUoemJqNd3DQACe6qIVjSo&hl=en&sa=X&ei=aLtwVKP4KYbDOcuTgcgI&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=E.%20A.%20Siddiq&f=false | title=Breaking the Yield Barrier | publisher=IRRI | date=1994 | accessdate=November 22, 2014}}</ref> 
* {{cite web | url=http://www.fao.org/docrep/003/X6905e/x6905e09.htm | title=Bridging the Rice Yield Gap in India | publisher=Food and Agriculture Organization | work=Scientific paper | date=2014 | accessdate=November 22, 2014}}

He has supervised 35 students in their PhD studies<ref name="INSA" /> and has delivered keynote addresses at many conferences.<ref name="Hybiz TV">{{cite web | url=http://www.hybiz.tv/EA-Siddiq--FRSF/165455 | title=Speech | publisher=Hybiz TV | date=2013 | accessdate=November 22, 2014}}</ref><ref name="Padmashree Prof Dr E A Siddiq" />

==Awards and recognitions==
Siddiq has received several honors starting with the Hari Om Ashram Trust National Award in 1976.<ref name="ABF" /><ref name="CDFD" /> In 1981, he was awarded the Vasvik Foundation Award, followed by Amrik Singh Cheema Award in 1988, Silver Jubilee Medal from the [[Directorate of Rice Research]] (DRR) in 1990<ref name="CDFD" /><ref name="INSA" /> and Om Prakash Bhasin Award in 1994.<ref name="ABF" /><ref name="CDFD" /> A year later, in 1995, he received the Norman Borlaug Award and the Rafi Ahmed Kidwai Award.<ref name="CDFD" /><ref name="ABF" /><ref name="INSA" /> Indian National Science Academy honored Siddiq in 1997 with the Silver Jubilee Medal.<ref name="ABF" /><ref name="CDFD" /><ref name="INSA" /> He has also received the GP Chatterjee Memorial Lecture Award<ref name="INSA" /> of the  Indian Science Congress Association in 2001, the Agricultural Leadership Award in 2008<ref name="ABF" /> and appreciative mementos from the [[Government of Tamil Nadu]] and the [[Government of Egypt]],<ref name="CDFD" /> besides receiving the Professor Sundar Lal Hora Medal of INSA, (2011) and B. P. Pal Memorial Award of National Academy of Agricultural Sciences (NAAS) (2011-12).<ref name="INSA" /> In 2011, the [[Government of India]] included him in the [[Indian honours system|Republic day honours]], listing him for the fourth highest civilian award of [[Padma Shri]].<ref name="ABF" /><ref name="Padma Shri" />

Siddiq is an elected Fellow of the [[National Academy of Sciences, India|National Academy of Sciences (India)]], Allahabad and [[National Academy of Agricultural Sciences]], New Delhi.<ref name="INSA" />

